<TITLE> Russia says US to respect its arms treaty concerns </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MOSCOW, Oct 28,(bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Russia expects to receive within days US proposals taking into account Moscow's concerns regarding a new strategic weapons deal negotiated by the two nations, Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov said on Tuesday. Russian and US negotiators have been working hard to produce a detailed treaty ready for signing by the two nations' leaders in December, when an existing pact known as START-1 regulating the number of long-range nuclear weapons expires. "The most important of these principles for us is the inter-connection between strategic offensive and defensive weapons, linked to a US programme of creating strategic weapons with non-nuclear charges," Russian news agencies quoted Lavrov as saying on board a plane heading from India to Russia. "On both issues, as we understand, the Americans heard our concerns, are ready to take them into account and promised that within days they would hand over their own proposals, addressing these problems." Quoting a statement issued in Washington, Russia's Itar-Tass news agency said White House National Security Adviser James Jones would visit Moscow on Oct. 28-29 to discuss the new strategic weapons deal. It gave no further details. Talks on the nuclear arms pact may have been facilitated by US President Barack Obama's decision to roll back plans of his predecessor George W. Bush to build a missile shield in Eastern Europe by deploying a radar in the Czech Republic and interceptor missiles in Poland. Moscow, which relies heavily on nuclear weapons for its defence because of the poor state of its conventional weapons, had fiercely opposed the planned anti-missile system. "There is a chance of agreeing on a new strategic weapons treaty by the moment the old one expires," Lavrov said. The current, landmark 1991 Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty (START-1) expires on Dec. 5. Lavrov said he believed the verification regime of the new nuclear arms treaty was "much lees rigid" compared to the old one